hands_on_practices.solution:
We start from the product of two slashed quantities built from the constant four-vector $A_{\mu}$:
$$(\gamma^{\mu}A_{\mu})(\gamma^{
u}A_{
u})=A_{\mu}A_{
u}\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u}.$$
Decompose the product of gamma matrices into symmetric (anticommutator) and antisymmetric (commutator) parts:
$$\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u}= rac{1}{2}\left(\{\gamma^{\mu},\gamma^{
u}\}+[\gamma^{\mu},\gamma^{
u}]ight).$$
Hence,
$$A_{\mu}A_{
u}\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u}= rac{1}{2}A_{\mu}A_{
u}\{\gamma^{\mu},\gamma^{
u}\}+ rac{1}{2}A_{\mu}A_{
u}[\gamma^{\mu},\gamma^{
u}].$$
Since $A_{\mu}A_{
u}$ is symmetric in the indices $\mu,
u$ while $[\gamma^{\mu},\gamma^{
u}]$ is antisymmetric, their contraction vanishes:
$$A_{\mu}A_{
u}[\gamma^{\mu},\gamma^{
u}]=0.$$
Using the Clifford algebra $\{\gamma^{\mu},\gamma^{
u}\}=2\eta^{\mu
u}I_{4}$, we obtain
$$A_{\mu}A_{
u}\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u}= rac{1}{2}A_{\mu}A_{
u}\cdot 2\eta^{\mu
u}I_{4}=\eta^{\mu
u}A_{\mu}A_{
u}I_{4}.$$
Recognizing the Lorentz-invariant scalar $A^{2}=\eta^{\mu
u}A_{\mu}A_{
u}$, the expression simplifies to
$$(\gamma^{\mu}A_{\mu})(\gamma^{
u}A_{
u})=A^{2}I_{4}.$$

We are given the Clifford algebra relation
$$
\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u} + \gamma^{
u}\gamma^{\mu} = 2 g^{\mu
u} I.
$$
For $\mu 
eq 
u$, the metric components satisfy $g^{\mu
u} = 0$, hence
$$
\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u} + \gamma^{
u}\gamma^{\mu} = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u} = -\,\gamma^{
u}\gamma^{\mu}.
$$
Let $T \equiv 	ext{tr}(\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u})$. By the cyclic property of the trace,
$$
T = 	ext{tr}(\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u}) = 	ext{tr}(\gamma^{
u}\gamma^{\mu}).
$$
Using the anticommutation result for $\mu 
eq 
u$,
$$
	ext{tr}(\gamma^{
u}\gamma^{\mu}) = 	ext{tr}(-\,\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u}) = -\,	ext{tr}(\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u}) = -T.
$$
Therefore,
$$
T = -T \quad \Rightarrow \quad 2T = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad T = 0.
$$
Thus, for $\mu 
eq 
u$, the trace $	ext{tr}(\gamma^{\mu}\gamma^{
u})$ is zero.
